A chemical plant explosion in Jilin, China, led to benzene flowing into the Songhua River, causing water pollution downstream in Harbin.
Officials shut down water supplies, prompting residents to stock up on essentials.
The government allocated funds to handle the crisis, while monitoring stations reported high benzene levels.
China informed Russia of the pollution, pledging cooperation.
Measures were taken to dilute pollutants and ensure public safety.
Efforts to minimize the impact on Russia include intensified monitoring and control measures.
The situation remains a top concern for both countries, with ongoing efforts to address the pollution.
